debrief_concerns: As to the topic of online dating in general, it is a completely skewed marketplace in which women are propositioned and showered with attention to an even higher degree than in real life. My experiences, some lay research and the observations of my friends  have generally born this out. Even marginally attractive women get dozens of messages a day while all men but the top 20% receive no responses for months and generally wind up feeling like they are trying to fill up the grand canyon by throwing stones. The sexual marketplace is already skewed by the biological reality of the female reproductive capacity being inherently more valuable. If all but one man in a tribe get killed, the tribe will survive. If all but one woman in the tribe die, the tribe is destined to extinction. Men compete and women choose. Taking this same dynamic online just exaggerates the reality of this and makes women even more picky, because they can field sexual advances from hundreds or thousands of men, rather than dozens. /  / This study was very interesting. Good luck with your research.

I didn't find the suggested strategy to be very different from what I usually do, which I've never thought of particularly as a strategy.  As I read through profiles I might be interested in, if I find traits I dislike, and once there are too many of those, or they are too severe, I just move on to another profile.  There are a lot more than three traits that I don't like, too...! /  / You didn't give us much instruction on how to choose the 20 people in the first place...  It really depresses me that OKCupid has changed so much now, that it is essentially the same as all the others.  I don't want to pick people based on just their pictures.  I want to see all messages that are sent to me, without having to approve the person first, based on their picture.  And sometimes I want to respond to a message that I don't like, so I don't want to first say I "like" that person. /  / I also don't think all OKC's changes had any effect on what they said their goal was - to get less mass mailings of spam.
